Rubrouck, and to persons in the 12th and 13th centuries styled as “de Rubrouck.”
A detailed notice of such documents was published by M. Edm. Coussemaker of Lille. See remarks by M. D’Avezac in Bull, de la Sοe. de Geοg., 2d vol. for 1868, pp. 569-570. It may be fairly assumed that Friar William came from this place; indeed, if attention had been paid to the title of the MS. belonging to Lord Lumley, which was published by Hakluyt (Itiuerarium fratris Willielini de Rubruguis de Ordinefratrum Minorum, Galli, Anno Gratiae 1253, cul partes Orientales), there need have been no question as to the traveller’s quasi-French nationality;
The country of Flanders was at this time a fief of the French crown (see Natalis de Wailly, Notes on Joinville, p. 576). William’s mother-tongue may probably have been Flemish. But this cannot be proved by his representation to Mangu Khan (p. 361) that certain Teutonici who had been carried away as slaves by a Tartar chief were nostroe linguae, as Dr Franz Schmidt inclines to think. but this (erroneously) has always been treated as if it were an arbitrary gloss of Hakluyt’s own.
